description:
Cyberplat was a company which made its profit from transferring payments from its cliens to telecom companies having its percent from these transactions. Here I was responsible for the whole database server implementing DBA and SA duties. The service was protected against failures by RAID and by standbys located on  geographically remote data centers. There was also configured alerting system which texted warnings on my mobile when some database parameters shows that something bad happening there. I always had my laptop with me in order to be able to connect and fix a problem even if it was out of working hours because it was viable for the business to have the service up around the clock and our system operated across the country with 11 time zones. The automatisation was leveraged by sh scripts. The common alerting was about standby lagging, or about free space, or some error emerged in alert log like ORA-600.

It was quite common task for me to roll out a brand new environment on a new host including installation of RH Linux. The new environment could be a testing one or another production standby. 

In the first place I used standbys as a protection against failures. For instance if there is a network problem and a productive database is unavailable then  I had an option to failover to its standby to keep our service up. Good old-fashioned standby is a very convenient tool to fulfill any productive hardware upgrade or repairing. I could switch over productive to a standby, do the repairing and switch the productive database back into its original datacentre. Another convenient property of this technology extensively used by me is the possibility to open a standby in read-only mode to make reports and eliminate IO pressure from a productive system.

When I came to work for this company most of database were 9.2 (one instance was even Oracle 7 run under obsolete version of Windows). It was 2012 and Oracle 11.2 was the robust. So our environment was virtually outdated and urgently needed upgrade. Those instances which could tolerate long downtime were upgraded over weekends. Of course it was thoroughly tested that their performance would not degrade after their upgrade to 11.2. To upgrade those instances that could not be down for a long while was used very convenient Golden Gate. It let me to configure cross-version replication where 9.2 is a primary and 11.2 is a target standby database so that the switchover happened in no time.

Also I dealt with Oracle bugs like incorrect query results. In these cases I proposed some workaround – how to rewrite the query in a such way that let it produce correct results, or applied patch.

Exact knowledge a source of an issue gives me a clue how to fix the problem. For instance, in my work I
widely use trace (event 10046). It gives me exact picture of what is happening. With help of trace I know the
most time-consuming operations and as a result I can choose the most appropriate measures to resolve the
issue. For example, it can be:
-- gathering fresh statistics, histogram creation;
-- query reorganisation;
-- changing access path of the query plan (the sequence or method of the join, indexes using in it);
-- index creation or rebuilding;
-- database parameters tuning;
-- reorganization of tables (partitioning, IOT etc);
-- as a last resort, plan stabilization.

